Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Dangote Flour, Guaranty Trust Bank Are Active

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-15T15:59:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-15/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-dangote-flour-guaranty-trust-bank.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for the
first day in three, adding less than 0.1 percent to 62.01 by the
3 p.m. close in Nairobi  Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  advanced for a third
day, increasing 1.2 percent to 778.93 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange  All-Share Index fell for
the first time in three days, declining 1 percent to 22,559.07
by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a  statement  on the
bourse’s website. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed for a second
day, adding 0.4 percent to 1,953.64 by the 1:30 p.m. close in
 Port Louis . The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index dropped for
the first time in three days, declining 0.4 percent to 1,175.87
by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Dangote Flour Mills Plc (DANGFLOU)  , a Nigerian producer,
closed at a 10-month low, losing 76 kobo, or the maximum daily
limit of 5 percent, to 14.4 naira. Full-year net income declined
to 2.72 billion naira ($17.7 million) from 5.56 billion naira a
year earlier, the company said in a statement published on the
website of the Nigerian Stock Exchange on Aug. 12.  Guaranty Trust Bank Plc (GUARANTY)  ,  Nigeria ’s second-
biggest lender by market value, closed at its highest in more
than a week, gaining 17 kobo, or 1.3 percent, to 13 naira. The
bank said first-half profit climbed 39 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
